Every few weeks someone asks me, politely, why they should pay for a hand-coded website when a page builder subscription costs less than lunch. It's a fair question, and it deserves a better answer than "because craft." So here it is — the honest version, including the cases where the page builder wins.

## What a page builder actually sells you

A page builder's product is not a website. Its product is *the feeling of building a website* — the drag, the drop, the instant preview. The website itself is a byproduct, and it shows in the output: markup generated by a machine that has to account for every possible thing you *might* drag, wrapped in divs upon divs, shipped with scripts for features you never used.

None of that is visible in the editor. All of it is visible to the two audiences that decide whether your site works: the person waiting for it to load, and the machines deciding whether to show it.

That's the trade you're making. Not money for pixels — the pixels look fine. You're trading away the quality of the underlying document, which happens to be the part search engines read.

## What hand-coded means (and doesn't)

When I say this studio hand-codes websites, I don't mean a developer typing every bracket by candlelight. I design the site, then write it in code with Claude — an AI that types faster than any developer I've hired, while I direct every decision. What "hand-coded" means is that the *output* is deliberate:

- **Every element exists because it's needed.** The page is HTML that says what it means — a heading is a heading, a list is a list. No wrapper soup.
- **The site is static.** Pages are finished documents before anyone requests them. Nothing to compute, nothing to hack, nothing to slow down as the plugin pile grows — because there is no plugin pile.
- **The invisible layer is exact.** Meta tags, structured data, Open Graph, sitemaps, an llms.txt index for AI assistants — placed by hand, per page, not approximated by an SEO plugin fighting the builder for control of the head tag.

The result is a site that loads instantly, ranks on its merits, and doesn't need feeding. This site works exactly that way, and you can [read how it's built](/work/palmadesign-io).

## "But I need to edit my own content"

The strongest argument for page builders used to be self-service editing, and it's now the most outdated one. Our sites ship with a content interface: you edit case studies, pages and posts in a friendly editor, press save, and the site rebuilds itself. You get the editing convenience without the builder rendering your markup. The code stays clean because you never touch it — and neither does a plugin.

## Where the page builder honestly wins

I promised the honest version, so: if your website is an experiment — a weekend idea, a landing page you'll kill in a month, a hobby that may not survive the year — use a builder. Speed-to-first-draft is genuinely theirs, and none of the debt matters if the site doesn't live long enough to pay it.

The math flips the moment the site *is* the business's front door. Debt compounds; craft compounds too, just in your favor.

## The three questions that decide it

1. **Will this site still exist in three years?** If yes, you'll pay the builder tax for three years — subscription, plugins, slowdowns, and eventually the redesign forced by the platform, not by you.
2. **Does search traffic matter to you?** If customers find you by searching — and increasingly, by asking AI assistants — the quality of your markup is a business input, not a technical nicety.
3. **Do you want to own it?** A hand-coded site is files. Yours. Move them anywhere, host them for pennies, hand them to any developer on earth. A builder site exists inside someone else's subscription — you're renting your own front door.

If you answered yes twice, the hand-coded route isn't the premium option. It's the cheaper one — it just invoices differently.

